5E2

Animal diversity = a + b1 x latitude + b2 x plant diversity

5E3

Time to PhD degree = a0 + b0 x amount of funding

Time to PhD degree = a1 + b1 x size of laboratory

Time to PhD degree = a2 + b2 x amount of funding + b3 x size of laboratory

b0 and b1 should be around 0; b2 and b3 should be larger than 0.

5M2

N   <- 100
rho <- 0.7
x1 <- rnorm(N)
x2 <- rnorm(N, rho*x1, sqrt(1-rho^2))
y  <- rnorm(N, mean=x1-x2)
d  <- data.frame(y=y, x1=x1, x2=x2)

lm(y ~ x1, data=d)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x1, data = d)
## 
## Coefficients:

##     -0.2391       0.3208

5M3

data("WaffleDivorce")
d <- WaffleDivorce

d$MedianAgeMarriage.s <- scale(d$MedianAgeMarriage)
d$Divorce.s <- scale(d$Divorce)

m.5M3 <- map(
  alist(
    Marriage ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
    mu <- a+bd*Divorce.s+ba*MedianAgeMarriage.s,
    a ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    bd ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    ba ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    sigma ~ dunif(0, 50)
  ),
  data=d)

plot(precis(m.5M3))

5M4

Mormon population by state information retrieved from https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/mormon-population-by-state.html

LDS <- read.csv("LDS.csv", header = TRUE)
LDS <- LDS[c("State", "Mormon.Percent")]
names(LDS) <- c("Location", "Mormon.Percent")
d <- merge(d, LDS, by="Location")

d$Marriage.s <- scale(d$Marriage)
d$Mormon.Percent.s <- scale(d$Mormon.Percent)

m.5M4 <- map(
  alist(
    Divorce ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
    mu <- a + ba*MedianAgeMarriage.s + br*Marriage.s + bm*Mormon.Percent.s,
    a ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    ba ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    br ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    bm ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    sigma ~ dunif(0, 50)
  ),
  data=d)

precis(m.5M4)

# Predict body weight using territory size
d$area.s <- scale(d$area)

m.5H1.1 <- map(
  alist(
    weight ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
    mu <- a+b*area.s,
    a ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    b ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    sigma ~ dunif(0, 50)
  ),
  data=d)

plot(precis(m.5H1.1))

area.seq <- seq(from=-3, to=3, length.out=100)
mu <- link(m.5H1.1, data=data.frame(area.s=area.seq))

5H3

# Model 1
d$avgfood.s <- scale(d$avgfood)

m.5H3.1 <- map(
  alist(
    weight ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
    mu <- a+bf*avgfood.s+bg*groupsize.s,
    c(a, bf, bg) ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    sigma ~ dunif(0, 50)
  ),
  data=d)

precis(m.5H3.1)
##        Mean StdDev  5.5% 94.5%
## a      4.53   0.10  4.36  4.69
## bf     0.76   0.24  0.37  1.14
## bg    -0.87   0.24 -1.26 -0.49
## sigma  1.12   0.07  1.00  1.23
plot(precis(m.5H3.1))

# Model 2
m.5H3.2 <- map(
  alist(
    weight ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
    mu <- a+bf*avgfood.s+bg*groupsize.s+bt*area.s,
    c(a, bf, bg, bt) ~ dnorm(0, 10),
    sigma ~ dunif(0, 50)
  ),
  data=d)

precis(m.5H3.2)
##        Mean StdDev  5.5% 94.5%
## a      4.53   0.10  4.37  4.69
## bf     0.50   0.29  0.04  0.96
## bg    -0.93   0.24 -1.32 -0.55
## bt     0.36   0.22  0.00  0.71
## sigma  1.10   0.07  0.99  1.22
plot(precis(m.5H3.2))

pairs(d[c("area", "groupsize", "avgfood", "weight")], col=rangi2)

  1. avgfood is a better predictor of body weight. Both when avgfood and area are included in separate models or in one model together, the coefficient for avgfood is larger. Also when thinking about the underlying causal mechanisms, it seems more likely that the higher the average amount of food available in an area, the more foods foxes will have access to, and more consumption leads to higher body weight.

  2. This is because avgfood and area are very strongly positively correlated. Multicollinearity may have influenced the results here.
